<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="5"><b>UAW puts unionists on trial at Freightliner</b></font><p>
<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">December 14, 2007 | Page 14</font><p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>MIKE GRIFFIN of the War Zone Education Foundation in Decatur, Ill., and an activist during the A.E. Staley lockout, looks at a battle in the UAW.</b><p>

WHILE TRADE unionists have focused on United Auto Workers (UAW) surrenders at Ford, Chrysler and General Motors that roll the clock back 50 years, nothing can be more telling about business unionism than the betrayal at Freightliner in Cleveland, N.C.<p>
The contract between Freightliner and UAW Local 3520, representing 4,200 employees, expired on March 31 of this year. Armed with a 98.4 percent strike vote, Local 3520 struck Freightliner.<p>
The media cried "wildcat strike," but that wasn't the case. The strike wasn't authorized by the International UAW, but it wasn't illegal, nor was it a wildcat strike.<p>
The local bargaining chairman was told by the company's human resources manager on April 2 that there was no contract extension. Later, at the beginning of the night shift, the plant production manager ordered all union workers to leave the plant, telling them there would be no disciplinary action, and they would not be penalized.<p>

